00:14:12,072 --> 00:14:13,313
but you can totally tell someone

261
00:14:14,013 --> 00:14:15,394
who someone is just based on their hair.

262
00:14:15,714 --> 00:14:18,736
So it's a really good way to get a lot of diversity.

263
00:14:19,416 --> 00:14:23,018
So we focused on hair texture, color, silhouette,

264
00:14:23,298 --> 00:14:24,519
all of these things that players use

265
00:14:24,539 --> 00:14:28,801
to reflect a player's style, race, and gender identity.

266
00:14:30,822 --> 00:14:37,087
We start off with a standard bald, but we also have a pompadour and a lot of hair colors

267
00:14:37,127 --> 00:14:40,329
that are not just like white people, only hair.

268
00:14:40,549 --> 00:14:42,111
So when you're making hair...

269
00:14:42,251 --> 00:14:45,794
Oh, I forgot I added that in there.

270
00:14:46,154 --> 00:14:48,596
This is an important hair option in all cases.

271
00:14:51,534 --> 00:14:55,559
Make the effort to make as many hair options for your players

272
00:14:55,599 --> 00:14:58,062
as possible, because hair is extremely diverse.

273
00:14:59,504 --> 00:15:01,687
And we got a lot of bang for our buck just by adding lots

274
00:15:01,727 --> 00:15:02,568
and lots of hair options.

275
00:15:05,368 --> 00:15:07,289
created a pre-selected color palette.

276
00:15:07,890 --> 00:15:09,691
And we did this for some specific reasons.

277
00:15:11,412 --> 00:15:13,434
We did not add a full color gradient

278
00:15:13,574 --> 00:15:15,656
so you could create any color skin

279
00:15:16,076 --> 00:15:18,458
because we wanted to be representational

280
00:15:18,698 --> 00:15:22,601
of skin colors specifically and not rainbows.

281
00:15:23,602 --> 00:15:25,223
And if you give someone the ability

282
00:15:25,263 --> 00:15:28,225
to pick one of 256 million colors,

283
00:15:28,505 --> 00:15:30,527
it becomes really hard to find something

284
00:15:30,547 --> 00:15:34,110
that actually you can kind of identify with.

285
00:15:34,590 --> 00:15:39,271
So instead, we tried to just develop a nice range of skin colors.

286
00:15:39,891 --> 00:15:43,192
And Leighton, here in the front, spent a long time going through

287
00:15:43,392 --> 00:15:47,633
and just making sure we had a diverse rainbow of flesh tones.

288
00:15:48,493 --> 00:15:51,194
This makes it really nice when you're actually building your character

289
00:15:51,234 --> 00:15:55,154
to quickly identify, like, oh, here's some nice colors that I want to look at.

290
00:15:55,315 --> 00:15:58,515
And I think Leighton went through and just kind of picked.

291
00:16:00,137 --> 00:16:03,100
I think every color in Dream Daddy is a beautiful color,

292
00:16:03,380 --> 00:16:04,801
and you can make a beautiful dad with it.

293
00:16:10,667 --> 00:16:15,068
Overall, we aimed to focus on stylization over realism.

294
00:16:15,348 --> 00:16:18,690
We didn't want our players to build an exact replica

295
00:16:18,710 --> 00:16:19,310
of themselves.

296
00:16:19,650 --> 00:16:21,651
We wanted them to build a cool dad Sona

297
00:16:21,691 --> 00:16:23,291
that they could identify with.

298
00:16:24,192 --> 00:16:27,533
Our goal was for people to self-identify and express

299
00:16:27,573 --> 00:16:28,033
themselves.

300
00:16:28,313 --> 00:16:31,134
So even though you can't tweak the focal distance

301
00:16:31,174 --> 00:16:34,155
between eyeballs or jowl depth, you

302
00:16:34,176 --> 00:16:36,476
can build a dad who looks cool.

303
00:16:44,401 --> 00:16:47,242
And that, I think, is probably one of the most effective uses

304
00:16:47,282 --> 00:16:49,043
of a character creator, saying, hey,

305
00:16:49,503 --> 00:16:51,964
this is a cool version of myself or something

306
00:16:52,004 --> 00:16:53,285
I aspire to be on screen.

307
00:16:54,926 --> 00:16:55,386
That's fun.

308
00:16:57,767 --> 00:17:01,048
Our next thing is fill in the blanks.

309
00:17:02,814 --> 00:17:06,679
After announcing Dream Daddy online, before it came out,

310
00:17:06,840 --> 00:17:08,462
there was a lot of excitement on the internet.

311
00:17:08,582 --> 00:17:09,864
People talked about it all the time.

312
00:17:10,385 --> 00:17:13,109
But there were also a few questions that came up.

313
00:17:13,810 --> 00:17:15,011
Frequently, this was one.

314
00:17:15,031 --> 00:17:17,235
I saw this a lot of.

315
00:17:18,242 --> 00:17:24,369
on Twitter. How do all of these gay dads have kids? And I think the expectation of the person

316
00:17:24,429 --> 00:17:30,816
asking this was usually to try and offer a counterpoint of like, this game's not possible

317
00:17:30,836 --> 00:17:35,701
because gay dads can't have kids. And that's silly.

318
00:17:37,340 --> 00:17:38,440
It's not 1999.

319
00:17:38,981 --> 00:17:41,682
There's tons of avenues for gay couples to become parents.

320
00:17:42,603 --> 00:17:44,744
And with Dream Daddy, we, of course,

321
00:17:44,884 --> 00:17:46,084
wanted to cater to that.

322
00:17:47,525 --> 00:17:49,646
If you've not played the game, Amanda

323
00:17:49,786 --> 00:17:51,087
is your dad's son's daughter.

324
00:17:51,467 --> 00:17:53,408
And one of the ways we wanted to answer this question

325
00:17:53,508 --> 00:17:56,230
was to have the player answer it for themselves.

326
00:17:57,150 --> 00:17:58,331
We're not in the business of telling you

327
00:17:58,791 --> 00:17:59,712
exactly how you're going to play.

328
00:18:00,232 --> 00:18:03,774
We want you to feel represented and included.

329
00:18:04,816 --> 00:18:08,097
So of course, the first answer is Amanda could be adopted,

330
00:18:09,178 --> 00:18:11,118
or she could be birthed by a surrogate,

331
00:18:12,599 --> 00:18:15,620
or birthed by a partner, like a cis-female one.

332
00:18:15,700 --> 00:18:17,281
Perhaps your dead sona is bisexual

333
00:18:17,421 --> 00:18:18,801
or previously had a female partner.

334
00:18:19,962 --> 00:18:22,262
Maybe it took them longer to come to terms

335
00:18:22,322 --> 00:18:23,223
with their sexuality.

336
00:18:23,763 --> 00:18:26,084
There's a lot of history and reasons why.

337
00:18:27,514 --> 00:18:29,095
A gay man might have a child.

338
00:18:29,355 --> 00:18:32,617
It could also be that your daughter was born by you

339
00:18:32,757 --> 00:18:37,141
if you are a trans male, or born by a partner

340
00:18:37,201 --> 00:18:37,961
who's a trans male.

341
00:18:38,842 --> 00:18:43,225
There are a lot of ways that couples can have children.

342
00:18:43,946 --> 00:18:45,927
And we wanted to cater to all of them.

343
00:18:46,708 --> 00:18:49,950
Some of these, though, start to bring

344
00:18:50,010 --> 00:18:52,572
in the question of a character, or your dad,

345
00:18:52,592 --> 00:18:54,854
Sona's sexual orientation.

346
00:18:54,894 --> 00:18:55,194
Because...

347
00:18:56,893 --> 00:18:59,215
just because your dad is dating other dads,

348
00:18:59,235 --> 00:19:01,737
that does not mean we should assume your dad, Sona, is gay.

349
00:19:02,237 --> 00:19:06,261
But we also kind of want to know if your dad is gay, bi,

350
00:19:06,321 --> 00:19:08,763
pansexual, sapiosexual, or heterosexual,

351
00:19:08,783 --> 00:19:11,165
who is maybe coming to new realizations.

352
00:19:12,406 --> 00:19:14,888
We wanted to make sure that, canonically, there

353
00:19:14,908 --> 00:19:17,150
was a way for the player to represent

354
00:19:17,570 --> 00:19:18,691
their diverse stories.

355
00:19:19,672 --> 00:19:20,573
This was important to us.

356
00:19:22,520 --> 00:19:24,901
Pretty quickly, when you start matching these up,

357
00:19:25,001 --> 00:19:26,222
some of them are interlinked.

358
00:19:26,842 --> 00:19:29,904
These options can turn into a complex decision tree

359
00:19:29,964 --> 00:19:31,865
with lots of edge cases.

360
00:19:33,326 --> 00:19:36,788
As I mentioned before, we had a small budget.

361
00:19:37,728 --> 00:19:37,908
Poor.

362
00:19:38,669 --> 00:19:40,450
This tree looks very expensive.

363
00:19:40,990 --> 00:19:43,851
It would be nice to cater to and have specific stories

364
00:19:43,891 --> 00:19:44,952
for every single case.

365
00:19:47,774 --> 00:19:48,435
We couldn't do that.

366
00:19:48,996 --> 00:19:51,139
So we had to ask ourselves, how do we

367
00:19:51,159 --> 00:19:53,422
allow people to explore this without getting

368
00:19:53,462 --> 00:19:54,303
into a crazy tree?

369
00:19:56,186 --> 00:19:58,089
Or worse, doing something like this.

370
00:19:59,470 --> 00:20:01,673
How many people have fun filling out one of these?

371
00:20:03,255 --> 00:20:04,397
Okay, one person. Great.

372
00:20:06,979 --> 00:20:08,161
Now, let me ask you this.

373
00:20:08,341 --> 00:20:11,184
Can you imagine filling out one of these for sexual preferences?

374
00:20:11,504 --> 00:20:14,167
I think it's already kind of awkward enough just for race,

375
00:20:14,648 --> 00:20:17,831
but I imagine that getting into the nitty gritty of something like this

376
00:20:18,592 --> 00:20:21,535
is even more awkward, and that's not necessarily an experience

377
00:20:21,635 --> 00:20:22,917
we want our player to have.

378
00:20:24,859 --> 00:20:27,100
this also can become technically complex.

379
00:20:28,001 --> 00:20:29,862
And it doesn't make sense narratively

380
00:20:29,942 --> 00:20:31,642
to all of a sudden have a questionnaire

381
00:20:31,682 --> 00:20:33,303
at the end of your character creator of like,

382
00:20:33,543 --> 00:20:35,684
hey, what's your sexual orientation?

383
00:20:35,704 --> 00:20:37,225
How's your daughter here?

384
00:20:37,265 --> 00:20:37,766
Fill us in.

385
00:20:38,966 --> 00:20:42,068
And we obviously don't want to make people feel categorized.

386
00:20:44,663 --> 00:20:46,645
The answer was narrative choices.

387
00:20:48,047 --> 00:20:51,911
We realized that it doesn't actually,

388
00:20:53,373 --> 00:20:56,136
we don't need to know your exact sexual orientation,

389
00:20:56,196 --> 00:20:58,719
we don't need to know Amanda's exact status

390
00:20:58,779 --> 00:21:01,322
of if she was born from surrogate or was adopted.

391
00:21:04,295 --> 00:21:10,919
born by you, but by making our questions part of the narrative and making the questions

392
00:21:10,979 --> 00:21:18,564
about Amanda and your relationship, we were able to, and keeping the questions simple,

393
00:21:19,084 --> 00:21:23,847
it leaves the door open for a lot of scenarios, and it keeps you involved in your universe

394
00:21:24,567 --> 00:21:25,188
of Dream Daddy.

395
00:21:25,268 --> 00:21:26,028
So we don't.

396
00:21:27,395 --> 00:21:30,516
deny a player's existence, we keep it open.

397
00:21:30,676 --> 00:21:33,537
This allows us to acknowledge the player's preferences

398
00:21:33,557 --> 00:21:35,497
without forcing them into a category.

399
00:21:36,838 --> 00:21:40,579
So instead, we ask you, what was your ex-partner?

400
00:21:41,760 --> 00:21:43,400
Did you call them father or mother?

401
00:21:44,220 --> 00:21:45,761
Or did Amanda call them father or mother?

402
00:21:46,161 --> 00:21:49,162
And we also ask you, you tell Amanda a story,

403
00:21:49,342 --> 00:21:51,503
and if it was a story about when she was born

404
00:21:51,703 --> 00:21:52,843
or when she was adopted.

405
00:21:54,024 --> 00:21:54,524
We do this.

406
00:21:55,524 --> 00:21:58,685
rather than in a questionnaire, in the actual game.

407
00:21:59,085 --> 00:22:01,425
So we use a narrative where you are looking

408
00:22:01,465 --> 00:22:02,946
through a series of old photographs,

409
00:22:04,046 --> 00:22:06,986
and you go through and you basically tell Amanda

410
00:22:07,086 --> 00:22:08,727
a series of stories about each photograph,

411
00:22:09,047 --> 00:22:11,567
which helps us build your character's past.

412
00:22:12,328 --> 00:22:14,108
I think this is ultimately more effective

413
00:22:14,368 --> 00:22:18,549
in creating your dad's sona's canon.

414
00:22:20,289 --> 00:22:21,649
than just filling out a questionnaire.

415
00:22:21,969 --> 00:22:24,150
And also it lends to some, I think,

416
00:22:24,210 --> 00:22:26,670
really beautiful and fun moments with Amanda,

417
00:22:26,730 --> 00:22:29,651
where it kind of brings you to this area

418
00:22:29,671 --> 00:22:30,791
of being a little sentimental

419
00:22:30,831 --> 00:22:32,231
and going through some old photographs

420
00:22:32,951 --> 00:22:34,872
with your daughter, who you love very much

421
00:22:34,932 --> 00:22:35,652
and want to protect.

422
00:22:38,452 --> 00:22:38,672
So,

423
00:22:41,953 --> 00:22:43,833
next we have number three.

424
00:22:44,934 --> 00:22:47,194
Enable your team with tools.

425
00:22:48,459 --> 00:22:56,883
This is, I think, very important if you are like me and like a white guy who's non-diverse.

426
00:22:57,804 --> 00:23:03,407
Something you can do is if you are in a position of leadership is make sure you're striving

427
00:23:03,507 --> 00:23:07,689
as best as possible to make sure that everyone is heard and enable everyone on your team

428
00:23:08,229 --> 00:23:13,892
to have access to creating and participating in the overall narrative and story of your

429
00:23:13,932 --> 00:23:14,132
game.

430
00:23:15,313 --> 00:23:17,135
With Dream Daddy, we had an evolving story

431
00:23:17,355 --> 00:23:18,696
that was regularly changing.

432
00:23:19,277 --> 00:23:22,680
And if we were building Dream Daddy using a node-based visual

433
00:23:22,720 --> 00:23:25,522
novel tool like Twine or Yarn or Fungus,

434
00:23:26,523 --> 00:23:27,824
we wouldn't necessarily have been

435
00:23:27,864 --> 00:23:29,746
able to explore our character development

436
00:23:30,767 --> 00:23:32,748
and make changes to the game simultaneously

437
00:23:32,788 --> 00:23:34,590
with our teeny weeny budget.

438
00:23:34,710 --> 00:23:37,252
Because the writers, Leighton and Vernon,

439
00:23:37,553 --> 00:23:38,594
would write something, and then we'd

440
00:23:38,634 --> 00:23:41,216
have to bring it into an engine and like,

441
00:23:42,056 --> 00:23:49,440
translate things and then add scripting for characters sliding across and actions and changing their expressions.

442
00:23:50,080 --> 00:23:53,602
Our writers would have been locked into time restraints with traditional dating sim tools,

443
00:23:54,483 --> 00:23:57,124
and whatever they wrote would have required extra build time.

444
00:23:57,224 --> 00:23:58,685
So this kind of sucks.

445
00:23:58,965 --> 00:24:03,467
But I found this really cool tool called Ink.

446
00:24:06,934 --> 00:24:07,734
I highly recommend it.

447
00:24:07,874 --> 00:24:10,235
It's super easy to use, kind of.

448
00:24:10,655 --> 00:24:12,435
I think Leighton sometimes has some,

449
00:24:13,095 --> 00:24:14,616
she had some problems with it crashing once,

450
00:24:14,716 --> 00:24:16,516
but that's fine, we figured it out.

451
00:24:16,936 --> 00:24:18,116
For the most part, it's a great tool.

452
00:24:18,616 --> 00:24:22,017
And it allowed our writers to have direct control of the game.

453
00:24:23,518 --> 00:24:25,138
The only problem is it was geared

454
00:24:25,258 --> 00:24:27,738
towards text-based games specifically,

455
00:24:28,038 --> 00:24:29,339
and we were building a visual novel.

456
00:24:30,359 --> 00:24:33,400
So, we created a tool called the DDML.

457
00:24:34,657 --> 00:24:39,420
compiler. This is the Dream Daddy markup language compiler. It's based on an altered version

458
00:24:39,620 --> 00:24:46,464
of Inc. syntax and it would allow us to generate every single scene in our game based on these

459
00:24:46,504 --> 00:24:50,847
scripts. It was inspired by things like Ruby on Rails, which means you could just hand

460
00:24:50,887 --> 00:24:54,790
it something and plop, there's everything in your scene. All of our animations, facial

461
00:24:54,830 --> 00:24:58,612
expressions, eggplants, it would parse through this and figure everything out and build it

462
00:24:58,652 --> 00:25:02,935
for you. Our entire Unity scene was just there. So look at that. Cool.

463
00:25:04,414 --> 00:25:07,255
That got built not by me, but it was generated.

464
00:25:08,756 --> 00:25:14,420
So our project became more agile.

465
00:25:14,560 --> 00:25:15,921
We could iterate through concepts easier

466
00:25:15,941 --> 00:25:17,002
than if we were building Dream Daddy

467
00:25:17,022 --> 00:25:18,222
with the standard visual novel tools.

468
00:25:18,683 --> 00:25:20,164
It allowed our story to keep changing

469
00:25:20,244 --> 00:25:22,405
while still making progress on the rest of the games.

470
00:25:23,226 --> 00:25:25,647
I stress that because diversity was something

471
00:25:25,667 --> 00:25:27,468
we were conscientious of, and that

472
00:25:27,488 --> 00:25:30,250
meant bringing in consultants with diverse points of view

473
00:25:30,670 --> 00:25:32,952
and sexualities to look at our script.

474
00:25:34,689 --> 00:25:37,811
So bring in experts and outside voices.

475
00:25:38,391 --> 00:25:39,491
This is always a good idea.

476
00:25:41,412 --> 00:25:44,533
We brought in lots of consultants,

477
00:25:44,873 --> 00:25:47,594
and it helped Leighton and Vernon know

